\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \fi0 \lquote I/you/he/she/it/we/you/they came.\rquote  \par
}\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \sb120 \fi0 {\s4\ql\sb240\sa60\keepn\f13\b\fs32 {\*\bkmkstart BMex_noappo1}2.2{\*\bkmkend BMex_noappo1}  No apposition\par
}\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \sb60 \fi0 In the mapping the interpersonal level to the representational level, apposition represents a one-to-many relation. This is not expected under transparency. Sri Lanka Malay is not transparent in this regard since it allows apposition. The following example shows an instance of apposition. The referents \i Mr Sebastian \i0 and {\i see\i0 } \lquote I\rquote  are introduced and subsequently refered to by the personal pronoun {\i kitham\i0 } \lquote we\rquote . \i Kitham \i0 alone is already sufficient on the representational level. However, {\i duuva\i0 } \lquote two\rquote  again refers to the same two referents in the world as does \i kitham\i0 ; we are dealing with apposition here.\par
\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 {}{ \par
