}\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \sb240 \fi0 {\s3\ql\sb240\sa60\keepn\f13\b\fs32 3  Representational-Morphosyntactic\par
}\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \sb180 \fi0 {\s4\ql\sb240\sa60\keepn\f13\b\fs32 {\*\bkmkstart BMex_gramrel_intro}3.1{\*\bkmkend BMex_gramrel_intro}  No grammatical relations (but semantic or pragmatic alignment)\par
}\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \sb60 \fi0 In the mapping between the representational level and the morphosyntactic level, some languages use an intermediate level of grammatical relations, which can change the direct mapping of semantic function on morphosyntactic expression. In Sri Lanka Malay, there are no grammatical relations, instead the semantic function (agent, patient, recipient, etc) is directly mapped onto morphosyntax, where it is expressed by case postpositions. The following example shows the use of the postpositions {\i =yang\i0 } \lquote {\scaps acc}\rquote , {\i =dering\i0 } \lquote {\scaps abl}\rquote  and {\i =nang\i0 } \lquote {\scaps goal}\rquote . The agent {\i incayang\i0 } \lquote he\rquote  is not marked by a postposition.\par
\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 {14cm}{ \par
()\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \fi0 Itthu baathu={\b yang} incayang Seelong={\b dering} laayeng nigiri={\b nang} as\u224?-baapi. \par
{\scaps \pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \fi0 dist} stone={\scaps acc} {\scaps 3s.polite} Ceylon-{\scaps abl} other country={\scaps dat} {\scaps cp}-bring\par
\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \fi0 { } {\scaps pat} {\scaps ag} {\scaps src} { } {\scaps goal} {\scaps v}\par
\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \fi0 \lquote He brought those stones from Ceylon to other countries.\rquote  (nosource) \par
}\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 Crucially, there is no way of changing the case postposition an argument takes. While the English Passive Alternation as in \i she beat him/he was beaten by her \i0 changes the marking of the patient from accusative to nominative and the marking of the agent from nominative to oblique \i by\i0 -agent, in SLM such operations do not exist. There is no possibility to promote of demote an argument morphosyntactically.\par
\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 {Nordhoff} (2009) has applied an array of tests for subjecthood to Sri Lanka Malay; none of the tests yielded evidence for the category \ldblquote subject\rdblquote  (or \ldblquote object\rdblquote ). For reasons of space, the tests will not be repeated here. However, the three traditional coding properties of subjects can briefly be discussed. These are agreement, word order and case marking. As discussed in Section {\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BMsec_crossref \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{2.1}}}, there is no agreement in SLM. Word order in SLM is generally verb-final, but the arguments of the verb can occur in any order to the left of the verb. This can already be seen from example ({\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BMex_gramrel_intro \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{3.1}}}), where we find the order {\scaps pat ag src goal v}. If word order were an important parameter, we would either expect the subject in initial position (SOV) or in direct vicinity of the verb (OSV). In ({\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BMex_gramrel_intro \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{3.1}}}), neither is the case. The best candidate for subjecthood, the pronoun \i incayang \i0 is neither in initial position nor adjacent to the verb. ({\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BMex_gramrel_intro \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{3.1}}}) thus already sheds doubt on word order as a criterion for grammatical relations. {Nordhoff} (2009) discusses variations in word order in more detail and concludes that word order in the preverbal field is completely free and cannot be used to establish grammatical relations. The last criterion is case marking. If we find that the only argument of an intransitive predicate (S) is always case-marked in the same way as either the actor (A) or the undergoer (P) of a transitive sentence, we have good arguments for subjecthood. This test also fails in SLM. The only argument of an intransitive predicate in SLM can be marked with either zero, {\i =yang\i0 } \lquote {\scaps acc}\rquote , {\i =nang/=dang\i0 } \lquote {\scaps dat}\rquote , or {\i =dering\i0 } \lquote abl\rquote .\par
