}\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \sb120 \fi0 {\s4\ql\sb240\sa60\keepn\f13\b\fs32 {\*\bkmkstart BMex_noappo_maccan}4.2{\*\bkmkend BMex_noappo_maccan}  No duplicate elements\par
}\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \sb60 \fi0 Transparent languages should encode information from the representational level exactly once, and note several time. This principle is violated by the SLM indefinite article \i hatthu\i0 . One occurrence would be enough to signal the unidentifiable status of the referent to the hearer, yet it is often found twice, as in ({\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BMex_noappo_maccan \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{4.2}}}). This is an intransparent mapping between the representational and the morphosyntactic level.\par
