\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \sb120 \fi0 {\s4\ql\sb240\sa60\keepn\f13\b\fs32 4.4  No raising\par
}\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \sb60 \fi0 In a transparent language, we would expect every argument to surface in the clause where it semantically belongs. Raising constructions like \i John seems to be intelligent \i0 are not transparent in the sense that \i John \i0 semantically is an argument of the lower clause but shows up in the higher clause in morphosyntax. Such structures are not found in Sri Lanka Malay.\par
\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \sb120 \fi0 {\s4\ql\sb240\sa60\keepn\f13\b\fs32 4.5  No grammatical gender, declination, conjugation\par
}\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \sb60 \fi0 A transparent language is not expected to have elements in morphosyntax which are not motivated on semantic grounds, i.e. elements whose form depends on arbitrary criteria like membership in a certain declension or conjugation class, or grammatical gender. Sri Lanka Malay has no declension or conjugation classes. There is no arbitrary gender assignment (as in German or French) either, even natural gender (sex-based classification) is very marginal. The only instance I am aware of is the pair {\i puthra\i0 } \lquote prince\rquote , {\i puthri\i0 } \lquote princess\rquote .\par
\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \sb120 \fi0 {\s4\ql\sb240\sa60\keepn\f13\b\fs32 4.6  No agreement (but pronominal arguments)\par
}\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \sb60 \fi0 As stated above in Section {\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BMsec_crossref \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{2.1}}}, there is no cross-reference, and thus no agreement.\par
\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \sb120 \fi0 {\s4\ql\sb240\sa60\keepn\f13\b\fs32 4.7  Phrase marking through clitics rather than head marking through affixes\par
}\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \sb60 \fi0 This is also what we find in SLM as discussed in Section {\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BMsec_functionmarking \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{3.3}}}.\par
\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \sb120 \fi0 {\s4\ql\sb240\sa60\keepn\f13\b\fs32 4.8  No fusional morphology\par
}\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \sb60 \fi0 Transparent languages are not expected to express more than one meaning per morpheme. This is to say that we do not expect any fused portmanteau forms. While in the great lines, SLM does not have fusional morphology, some allomorphs of case markers could be analyzed as portmanteau forms. This is the case for the allomorph \i =dang \i0 of the dative marker \i =nang\i0 . This is obligatory for the monosyllabic pronouns {\i see\i0 } \lquote 1s\rquote , {\i goo\i0 } \lquote 1s\rquote , {\i luu\i0 } \lquote 2s\rquote , {\i dee\i0 } \lquote 3s\rquote . Another instance is the allomorph \i =ppe \i0 of the possessive marker \i =pe\i0 , which attaches to the same four items. One can then postulate that both \i =dang \i0 and \i =ppe \i0 carry a meaning of {\scaps singular} and {\scaps pronoun} besides their normal case semantics. This means that more than one meaning is expressed in one form, an instance of fusional morphology.\par
\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \sb240 \fi0 {\s3\ql\sb240\sa60\keepn\f13\b\fs32 5  Morphosyntactic/Phonological\par
}\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \sb180 \fi0 {\s4\ql\sb240\sa60\keepn\f13\b\fs32 5.1  Phonological phrasing and morphosyntactic phrasing run parallel\par
}\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \sb60 \fi0 In the interface between morphosyntax and phonology, a transparent mapping is found if there is a 1:1 correspondence between morphosyntactic phrasing and phonological phrasing. The Major morphosyntactic consituent in Sri Lanka Malay are the clause CLS, the predicate PRED and the noun phrase NP. NPs are not restricted to nominal heads. Indeed, numerals, adjectives, pronouns, deictics, quantifiers, and even sentences and utterances can head NPs without further measures being taken. This means that the normal structure of the clause can be represented as NP* PRED. On the phonological level, {Nordhoff} (2009) distinguishes Presuppositive Phrases with a LH boundary tone from Assertive Phrases with a L boundary tone. There seems to be a 1:1 mapping of NPs on Presuppositive Phrases, and PRED on Assertive Phrases, so that the phrasing runs parallel on both levels and is therefore transparent.\par
\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \sb120 \fi0 {\s4\ql\sb240\sa60\keepn\f13\b\fs32 {\*\bkmkstart BMex_rightextraction_quot}5.2{\*\bkmkend BMex_rightextraction_quot}  Phonological weight does not influence morphosyntactic placement\par
}\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \sb60 \fi0 A dramatically transparent language would completely ignore phonological weight when determining the order of constituents. Constituent order would be solely determined by semantics. This is not the case for SLM. While normally all arguments are preverbal, very heavy constituents can be shifted to postverbal position. This is frequently found for reported utterances ({\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BMex_rightextraction_quot \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{5.2}}}), but other constituents can also be shifted, for instance the complement of a modal in ({\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BMex_rightextraction_modal \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{5.2}}}).\par
